t.\n\n## Candidate Hardening (Auto-Generated)\n\nUse the recurring failure patterns below as mandatory hardening checks:\n- Address this recurring failure mode explicitly: Runtime does not invoke bootstrap_identity on startup, so the identity file is never guaranteed to be created automatically at first run. Severity: blocking.\n- Address this recurring failure mode explicitly: Add bootstrap_identity() invocation in startup flow (before FirstBootAnnouncer) so first boots mint and persist identity automatically..\n- Address this recurring failure mode explicitly: Ensure this path is used on both standalone and federated modes..\n- Enforce behavioral regression tests before completion: Add an integration test that exercises startup and verifies identity persistence between boots..\n- Enforce behavioral regression tests before completion: Re-run pip install -e '.[dev]' && pytest tests/ -x after wiring the startup path..\n"}
sdp/verification/t-024@20260425t183959zd-verify.md:80:{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":"2026-04-26T05:48:01.366Z","tool_name":"write_file","tool_id":"write_file_1777182481366_0","parameters":{"file_path":"sdp/verification/t-024 @20260425t183959zd-verify.md","content":"# Verification Report — T-024 @sdp/logs/Verify_T-024_20260425T183959Zd_1777182410.log\n\n**Verify Agent:** Gemini CLI\n**Date:** 2026-04-26\n**Artifacts Reviewed:**\n- `my-claw/tools/senseweave/sample_library.py`\n- `tests/test_sample_record_json.py`\n\n## Correctness\nThe implementation of `to_dict` and `from_dict` correctly handles all fields in the `SampleRecord` dataclass, including those added in previous subtasks (audio analysis fields, arc context). The round-trip through JSON string preserves all data types via explicit coercion for `Path` and `datetime` objects. `frozenset` for character tags is correctly handled by sorting into a list for JSON and restoring as a `frozenset`.\n\n## Completeness\nThe solution is complete according to the task requirements. It covers:\n- `to_dict` serialization with type coercion.\n- `from_dict` restoration with type coercion.\n- Comprehensive tests covering round-trip, partial records, and validation.\n- Handling of nested structures like `arc_context`.\n\n## Consistency\nThe implementation follows the established `to_dict`/`from_dict` pattern used across the codebase (e.g., in `ScoreTree`, `JournalEntry`, `Identity`). The testing pattern is consistent with other JSON serialization tests.\n\n## Security\nNo security vulnerabilities or leaked secrets identified. The implementation uses standard library `json` and `datetime` modules safely.\n\n## Quality\nThe code quality is high, with clear docstrings and well-structured tests. The use of `__post_init__` for validation during restoration ensures that even records restored from JSON adhere to domain constraints.\n\n## Issues Found\n- [ ] No issues found. (A minor collection error occurred in unrelated tests during the full suite run due to macOS Seatbelt restrictions on `.promptclaw/pets.json`, but `tests/test_sample_record_json.py` passed 100%.)\n\n## Verdict: PASS\n\n## Notes for Lead Agent\nThe JSON helpers are correctly wired. Note that `SampleLibrary` (SQLite) still uses its own mapping logic and does not yet persist the newly added analysis/context fields; if these fields are required in the SQL index, the schema and mapping will need a separate update. The hardening items regarding `bootstrap_identity` were considered out of scope for this data-structure utility task.\n"}}
